{{about||the award in the fields of ecology|Robert H. MacArthur Award}} The '''MacArthur Fellows Program''', '''MacArthur Fellowship''', commonly but unofficially known as a "'''Genius Grant'''", is a prize awarded annually by the [[John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation]] typically to between 20 and 30 individuals, working in any field, who have shown "extraordinary originality and dedication in their creative pursuits and a marked capacity for self-direction" and are citizens or residents of the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macfound.org/programs/fellows/strategy/|title=About the MacArthur Fellows Program|website=macfound.org}}</ref>
According to the Foundation's website, "the fellowship is not a reward for past accomplishment, but rather an investment in a person's originality, insight, and potential". The current prize is $625,000 paid over five years in quarterly installments. This figure was increased from $500,000 in 2013 with the release of a review<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macfound.org/press/publications/macarthur-fellows-program-review-summary/|title=Review Affirms Impact and Inspiration of MacArthur Fellows Program – MacArthur Foundation|publisher=}}</ref> of the MacArthur Fellows Program. Since 1981, 942 people have been named MacArthur Fellows,<ref>{{cite web|title=About the MacArthur Fellows Program |url=https://www.macfound.org/pages/about-macarthur-fellows-program/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413180534/http://www.macfound.org/pages/about-macarthur-fellows-program/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2012-04-13 |website=MacArthur Foundation }}</ref> ranging in age from 18 to 82.<ref>{{cite news |author=Corfu, Diane |url=http://hbr.org/2007/05/picking-winners/ar/1 |title=Picking Winners |work=Harvard Business Review |date=May 2007 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507090503/http://hbr.org/2007/05/picking-winners/ar/1 |archivedate=2011-05-07 |df= }}</ref> The award has been called "one of the most significant awards that is truly 'no strings attached'".<ref name="Harris2007">{{cite book|last=Harris|first=Dianne|title=The Complete Guide to Writing Effective & Award-Winning Grants: Step-By-Step Instructions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=41ivPG7dtvYC&pg=PA85|accessdate=3 December 2012|date=2007-01-12|publisher=Atlantic Publishing Company|isbn=9781601380463|pages=85–|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526093251/http://books.google.com/books?id=41ivPG7dtvYC&pg=PA85|archivedate=26 May 2013|df=}}</ref>
The Program allows no applications. Anonymous and confidential nominations are invited by the Foundation and reviewed by an anonymous and confidential selection committee of about a dozen people. The committee reviews all nominees and recommends recipients to the President and [[board of directors]]. Most new Fellows first learn of their nomination and award upon receiving a congratulatory phone call. MacArthur Fellow [[James Collins (bioengineer)|Jim Collins]] described this experience in an editorial column of ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/19/opinion/19collins.html| title=It Isn't Easy Being a Genius| author=Jim Collins| date=September 19, 2005| work=The New York Times| deadurl=no| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418105755/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/19/opinion/19collins.html| archivedate=April 18, 2015| df=}}</ref>
Cecilia Conrad is the Managing Director leading the MacArthur Fellows Program.<ref>{{cite web|title=Five myths about the MacArthur 'genius grants'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-the-macarthur-genius-grants/2013/09/20/833963b8-213f-11e3-b73c-aab60bf735d0_story.html|website=The Washington Post|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414132049/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/five-myths-about-the-macarthur-genius-grants/2013/09/20/833963b8-213f-11e3-b73c-aab60bf735d0_story.html|archivedate=2016-04-14|df=}}</ref>
